# Number of titles added to Netflix over the years
Netflix['year_added'] = Netflix['date_added'].dt.year
titles_added_per_year = Netflix['year_added'].value_counts().sort_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x=titles_added_per_year.index, y=titles_added_per_year.values)
plt.title('Number of Titles Added to Netflix Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Titles Added')
plt.xticks(rotation=90
          )
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Generate word cloud for titles
title_text = ' '.join(Netflix['title'])
title_wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, background_color='white').generate(title_text)

# Plot word cloud for titles
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.imshow(title_wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.title('Word Cloud of Netflix Titles')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

In [31]:
# Assuming 'duration' column format is like '1 Season' or '90 min'
# Extract numeric values from 'duration' column
Netflix['duration_numeric'] = Netflix['duration'].str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float)

# Map 'TV Show' to 1 and 'Movie' to 0
Netflix['type_numeric'] = Netflix['type'].map({'TV Show': 1, 'Movie': 0})

# Calculate average duration for each type
average_duration = Netflix.groupby('type')['duration_numeric'].mean()

# Plot the comparison
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.barplot(x=average_duration.index, y=average_duration.values, palette='Set2')
plt.title('Average Duration of Movies vs. TV Shows')
plt.xlabel('Type')
plt.ylabel('Average Duration')
plt.show()
